data.content:
Three things break. Here's each one with the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

All that manual `Expression.Lambda`/`Expression.Call` code **won't compile**. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
// .NET 10 — no expression tree needed
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

---

### 2. Complex type column names are now uniquified/use full paths

Two changes hit you:

- **Duplicate property names** (`ShippingAddress.Street` & `BillingAddress.Street`) now get a numeric suffix appended automatically.
- **Nested complex types** (`Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City`) now map to `Payment_BillingAddress_City` instead of `BillingAddress_City`.

Both generate column-rename migrations. To **keep the old names**, pin them explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, a =>
        a.Property(addr => addr.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, a =>
        a.Property(addr => addr.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street"));
});

// For nested complex types — preserve the old shorter name
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, a =>
            a.Property(addr => addr.City)
             .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City")));
});
```

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on this interface gained a `string logCommandText` parameter. Add it:

```csharp
public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
    IRelationalConnection connection, DbCommand command,
    DbContext context, Guid commandId, Guid connectionId,
    DateTimeOffset startTime,
    string logCommandText)          // ← new parameter (redacted SQL)
{ /* logging — use logCommandText for safe logging */ }
```

Update **all** implemented methods (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.

---

**Bonus:** Also set an explicit `Application Name` in your connection string — EF Core 10 now auto-injects version info otherwise, which can split connection pools and leak stack details.
